CS 384g Final Project: Augmented Reality
Fall 2007
Adrian Quark

http://www.cs.utexas.edu/~quark/cs384g_p4/writeup.html

FEATURES
------------------------------------------------------------------------

- Use Burns' line extraction algorithm to extract straight lines
- Use graph algorithms to identify rectangles
- Euler's method for simulating a particle system
- Physically accurate wall-particle collision detection

USAGE
------------------------------------------------------------------------

There are three programs included:

pose
	Extract rectangles, do pose estimation, and display the camera and
	rectified image in world coordinates. Drag the mouse in the 3D window
	to rotate the view.

physics
	Simulate ball rolling in a maze. Drag the mouse in the 3D window to
	rotate the view. Use the following keys to accelerate the ball (these
	are designed for a Dvorak keyboard layout):

	h: accelerate left
	n: accelerate right
	c: accelerate forward
	t: accelerate back

sim
	Augmented reality simulation combining pose estimation and physics.
	Keys:

	a: set neutral position
	m: toggle mirroring of image

PREREQUISITES
------------------------------------------------------------------------

The Glorious Glasgow Haskell Compilation System, version 6.8.1
   http://www.haskell.org/ghc/

HOpenGL 2.2.1.1
   http://www.haskell.org/haskellwiki/Opengl

HMatrix 0.1
   http://alberrto.googlepages.com/gslhaskell

easyVision
   http://alberrto.googlepages.com/easyvision

BUILDING
------------------------------------------------------------------------

1. Download and install the prerequisites. The Makefiles expect easyVision to
   be installed in the ./easyVision directory.

2. Edit the following Makefiles to use the correct paths for your system:
   ./Makefile
   ./burns/Makefile
   ./easyVision/lib/ImagProc/Segments/Makefile

3. Run make
